---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import StochasticHero from '../components/StochasticHero.astro';
import { site } from '../data/site';
---

<BaseLayout description={site.description} bodyClass="page-home">
  <StochasticHero />

  <div class="page-wrap fade-trail">
    <section class="prose about-section">
      <h2>About</h2>
      <p>
        Understanding how stochastic processes shape infection is critical because
        population-level measurements hide cell-to-cell and tissue-scale variability. I am an
        infectious disease computational biologist with a BS in mathematics and physics and a PhD
        in computational biology. My work asks how birth–death, inheritance, and rare-state
        switching determine host–pathogen outcomes, and how those dynamics can be read from
        single-cell and spatial transcriptomes.
      </p>
      <p>
        At OHSU / ONPRC, I build integrative frameworks for spatial and single-cell data in
        nonhuman primate models of SIV and <em>Mycobacterium tuberculosis</em>. These systems
        connect local cellular state to tissue organization, which makes it possible to ask whether
        rare infected or immune states persist, spread, or resolve across scales. Alongside that
        work, I develop open tools for navigating immune and viral gene spaces.
      </p>
      <p>
        Earlier, I used Gillespie-style and agent-based models to study stress signaling and
        antibiotic tolerance in <em>E. coli</em>, where molecular fluctuations link to slower
        physiological outcomes. That scale-bridging approach continues to organize how I interpret
        infection and immunity.
      </p>
      <p class="meta" style="margin-top: 1.5rem">{site.location}</p>
    </section>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
